This film is set in the beautiful desert landscape of Gujarat, India. The colors and glory of the place is beautifully captured in the subtle glow of ochre and orange hues by Oscar winning cinematography Russel Carpenter (Titanic). This film explores the ideas of tradition, culture, misogyny in the heart of rural India through the experiences, adventures and escapades of four compelling women and their friendships that tug at our humanity. Director Leena Yadav excels at story telling and compassionately frames the lives of her characters instantly transporting us to that place and time. Stellar performances by Radhika Apte, Tanisha Chatterjee , Surveen Chawla, Mahesh Balraj, Adil Hussain, Riddhi Sen, Lehar Khan and Sayani Gupta. A powerful, yet humorous, uplifting film lending nuance to the serious topic of patriarchy. Join me on Zoom for a discussion with Leena Yadav and cast on the film. 17:24:03","updated":"2022-01-06 20:47:32","type":"photo","description":"335,000 likes in 24 hours. This was a lot to process. The first time this image went viral was back in 2016. It was quite overwhelming. It helped raise awareness of the #NODAPL movement, but going viral brings a full spectrum of attention, both good and bad. In 2016, I was lucky to be using a code name, so nobody actually knew who took the photograph. The code name was used while I covered the movement to focus on the movement itself and not me as a photographer. The story wasn’t about me. It was about protecting the water and Indigenous rights. I used the name Redhawk, a name Tom Goldtooth jokingly gave me one night in the media tent. I eventually became known as that through camp and the Water Protector community. I caught flak for that name from some, with people thinking I was trying to portray myself as native, but that was never my intention. The other day, I made this tweet. I had a little less than 1,000 followers on my IG. Mostly friends and family and supporters. A small group. I had no idea this would go viral. Thankful it did and helped raise awareness. When I woke up yesterday and saw what was happening, I rushed to the tweet and laced it with info and Indigenous resources. I spoke about #FreeRedFawn and the proud Lakota WOMAN on the horse. I shared Indigenous led groups people should follow. This photo is important, but just a small part of a story that isn’t mine to tell. We don’t get to choose when we go viral. There is no magic button that controls when the internet takes a hold of something. When things do go viral, however, it can hit you like a ton of bricks. It isn’t pleasant. It’s often stressful and you become a target for the full wrath of the internet at times. Regardless, I’m thankful this photo and the powerful woman warrior on Sunshine (the horse) can help impact and raise awareness around #NODAPL. Massive love to my Water Protector family. We ride together forever. BSK.\n\nThose of you that have followed this page know how this spotlight and the NODAPL movement drove me to alcoholism and nearly suicide. Thankful to say I have been sober for 9 months, ever since you all reached out and helped me. \n\nI love y’all. For real. 15:20:19","updated":"2021-07-16 09:49:04","type":"photo","message":"Helping the community through front porch photo sessions during the pandemic BY SUMI CHAUDHARY (Rashmi Chaudhary) Looking back, I remember that I had back to back photo shoots scheduled on the weekend of March 14. I went ahead with those shoots, not knowing what the future held. We were just learning about the coronavirus at that time, and so I self-isolated for a couple of days after the shoot to keep my family safe. Then, a state of emergency was declared that weekend and we went into a lockdown. At first, I looked upon the lockdown as a blessing in disguise, because it gave me some time to unwind and to spend with my family. However, weeks turned into months with little signs of the virus slowing down. Some of my well-wishers kept checking in on me regularly. They also suggested the idea of doing socially distanced “front porch sessions” to capture the images of the community during lockdown. I was apprehensive about going out into the community given that there were so many unknowns with the pandemic, but the seed had been planted, and the idea continued to grow in my mind. In mid-April, as a way of giving back to our frontline healthcare workers, a few of my friends and I organized a lunch for the emergency department staff at Northside Hospital. Doing that motivated me to give back even more! It gave me the courage to face my fears, step out of my house, and use my photography skills to capture some smiling faces! I started doing the front porch photo sessions in my subdivision and soon received enquiries from other subdivisions in the neighborhood. The feedback I received, session after session, was that it had been a fun activity for the entire family to dress up and have their photos taken. The feeling was mutual. I am a people person and it had been hard staying at home during the lockdown. The happiness I got from capturing the families through my photos inspired me to do more and to give back to the community! I donated half of the money I made from the front porch sessions to the Northside Hospital’s lunch program for frontline workers and to Food4lives. Soon, I started doing outdoor portrait shoots for expectant mothers and seniors, making sure to follow the CDC social distancing guidelines by keeping my physical distance and by wearing a mask for my safety and theirs! You can find more photos from my front porch sessions on my Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/sumisthirdeye/ and Instagram profile https://www.instagram.com/sumicsumic/ - Coordinated by Navami 14:51:49","updated":"2021-11-16 11:58:45","type":"link","title":"EVACUATION-FLIGHT","caption":"airindia.in","description":"EVACUATION FLIGHT","message":"Sharing travel experience to India during current Covid19 situation - hope it helps anyone intending to travel. All international travel to and from India is currently banned due to Covid19 situation. If you have an emergency situation then you will need to register your request for travel with the Indian Embassy, here is the website - https://www.indianembassyusa.gov.in/News?id=24970 You are required to signup to quarantine yourself in a private hotel after landing in India for up to 14 days (minimum 7 days if you test negative) at your own cost. You will be required to provide a cell phone number where you can be tracked through Aarogya setu app. If you qualify (first priority Indian Nationals next OCI card holders) then an Indian Embassy representative will contact you regarding travel on one of the Air India evacuation flights. In my case I was contacted on a Thursday for traveling on that Saturday & asked to decide within 3 hours. It is a one way flight & fares are expensive, for e.g Chicago-Bengaluru cost $1438/-. Evacuation flights are not the same as usual flights. There is no service, a face mask, face shield, hand sanitizer pouches, a couple of boxed sandwich meals & a couple of water bottles are placed at your seat for use throughout the flight. After landing in India, the local state government quarantine rules apply. In Bengaluru, everyone that landed was asked to decide between their hotel choices (For e.g. single occupancy rates budget hotel - Rs 1200/per day, 3 star - Rs 1850/per day, 5 star - Rs 4100/per day) & bused there for a 7 day stay. Elderly (above 80) & kids (under 10 accompanied by a parent) are tested and sent for a home quarantine the same day. For return back to US, if you are a US citizen and would like to be accommodated on US repatriation flight, register yourself on US Embassy web site - https://step.state.gov/ Air India operates the repatriation flights and you can book online, here is the link- http://www.airindia.in/evacuation-flight.htm However the flights get all booked within a half hour of opening the day they are announced, so good luck! Economy flight costs about Rs 1.2 lacs one way. KLM, Delta & Lufthansa were operating unscheduled flights until June...they may still be. These flights are tentative until DCGA approval 4 days before the flight. You are required to be all geared up in the ppe suit, face mask, face shield during travel back as well, so quite uncomfortable. Same drill with meal packages as well (better to carry your own couple of Chapatis/rotis to be safer). 34152555_3040951079336231","platform":"Facebook","date":"2020-07-09 20:46:05","updated":"2021-11-23 13:16:43","type":"photo","description":"“We came to America when I was two. My father worked as an engineer for a bunch of different tech companies. I’ve always felt like an American. My parents told me that I could be anything I wanted. I do remember them saying I couldn’t get a job when I turned sixteen, but I assumed it was a typical Indian household protecting their daughter. So I focused all my energy into making good grades and getting into college. I finished my applications early. But when I showed them to my mom, she zoned in on one particular part. ‘Be sure to mark that you’re an international student,’ she said. She explained that because of my H4 visa status, the selection process would be much tougher. And I wouldn’t qualify for financial aid. I was devastated. I’d done everything right. I took 14 honors classes. I was 4th in my class. I was even a national champion in artistic roller skating. But none of that seemed to matter. There was a chance I couldn’t even go to college in America. I cried for the entire day, and for the rest of the year my mental health took a really bad hit. I’d wake up in the middle of the night—worried about my future. A lot of those fears didn’t come true. But it has been tough. I was waitlisted at all my top choices. I ended up getting into a good school, but I couldn’t study the arts like I wanted. I couldn’t have the social life I wanted. I’ve had to make every decision based on what gives me the best chance of staying in the country. It’s like I’m always playing a game. And if I mess up once, I’ll need to leave. For a long time I carried a lot of anger. I was jealous of my younger brother for being born here. I was mad at my parents for not telling me. But both of them were born in a village. They gave up so much to be here. They went years at a time without seeing their families. How could I be mad when they sacrificed so much? I think they were afraid of discouraging me. They were focused on me being OK in the moment, and they assumed it would all work out. The American Dream is so well marketed. And when you get here, it feels so close. Like if you just work hard—everything will fall into place. And I think that’s what they always believed for me.”","message":"HONY covers H4 kids Pradesh and Bihar.\nIt is a series of festivals that occur during the Hindu month of Shravana or Sawan and Bhadrapada or Bhado, that corresponds to the Indian monsoon season of July - August - September. Haryali Teej, Kajari Teej and Hartalika Teej welcome the monsoon season and are celebrated primarily by girls and women, with songs, dancing and prayer rituals. Teej is marked by fasting of women who pray to Lord Shiva and Goddess Parvati seeking their blessings for marital bliss. Swings are put on trees for girls. 01:18:35","updated":"2021-06-07 20:53:32","type":"status","message":"Once, Lord Indra got upset with Farmers, he announced there will be no rain for 12 years & you won’t be able to produce crops. Farmers begged for clemency from Lord Indra, who then said, Rain will be possible only if Lord Shiva plays his Damru. But he secretly requested Lord Shiva not to agree to these Farmers & when Farmers reached Lord Shiva he repeated the same thing that he will play Damru after 12 years. Disappointed Farmers decided to wait till 12 years. But one Farmer regularly was digging, treating & putting manure in the soil & sowing the seeds even with no crop emerging. Other Farmers were making fun of that Farmer. After 3 years all Farmers asked that Farmer why are you wasting your time n energy when you know that rains will not come before 12 years. He replied “I know that crop won’t come out but I’m doing it as a matter of “practice”. After 12 years I will forget the process of growing crops and working in the field so I must keep it doing so that I’m fit to produce the crop the moment there is rain after 12 years.” Hearing his argument Goddess Parvati praised his version before Lord Shiva & said “You may also forget playing the Damru after 12 years!” The innocent Lord Shiva in his anxiety just tried to play the Damru, to check if he could… and hearing the sound of Damru immediately there was rain and the farmer who was regularly working in the field got his crop emerged immediately while others were disappointed. It is the practice which keeps on making you perfect. We become even diseased or old just because we don’t practice. Practice is the essence of quality survival. So, let lockdown lift after 2 weeks, 2 months or 2 years. Whatever trade or profession we are in, keep sharpening our skills, practice with what we have, upgrade our knowledge.
